occurrenceRemarks: Branching pattern rather open. The central leader coninues growth, and the branches are axillary- alternate or sometimes sub-whorled, but develop from the old wood, not from behind a resting bud. Inflorescences terminate 1-year old laterals, which may be up to 30 cm long but more usually 5-10 cm, and are pendent. The perianth parts are very broad and stout, with a long limb, and both styles and perianth are persistent in the fruit. Branches are all axillary and usually whorled, but they develop from nodes that are 2-3 years old.

occurrenceRemarks: Stems whorled or single. The inflorescences are borne in two positions. Some are terminal to whorl-laterals. When in this position a single branch usually develops immediately behind the inflo [inflorescence] and grows on. The fruit then appears sessile on the branch. More commonly, inflorescences are borne sessile, sometimes clustered, usually at or near a whorl. Thus all or nearly all of the infructescences are sessile on old wood. This is quite different from var. cernuella. The bark also is diferent- thin, red and peeling in papery flakes in var. nutans.

occurrenceRemarks: Branching pattern rather open. The central leader coninues growth, and the branches are axillary- alternate or sometimes sub-whorled, but develop from the old wood, not from behind a resting bud. Inflorescences terminate 1-year old laterals, which may be up to 30 cm long but more usually 5-10 cm, and are pendent. The perianth parts are very broad and stout, with a long limb, and both styles and perianth are persistent in the fruit. Branches are all axillary and usually whorled, but they develop from nodes that are 2-3 years old.
